Handling Time and Date¶

  • datetime foundations in Python and Numpy
  • the Pandas timestamp and Datetime index
  • up and downsampling with resample() and asfreq()
  • interpolation and Aggregation
  • Rolling Windows and Moving Averages

The Python datetime Module¶

datetime is a module that comes with Python Standard Library. datetime is used to manipulate dates and times.

In [1]:
#from datetime module import the date class
from datetime import date

A date is characterized by year-month and day

In [2]:
#create date object 
#date(year,month,day)
date_A = date(2020 , 4 , 25)
In [3]:
date_A
Out[3]:
datetime.date(2020, 4, 25)
In [4]:
type(date_A)
Out[4]:
datetime.date

Why do we need a datetime object¶

But why not store dates like this :

In [5]:
A = "2020 , 4 , 25"

Because date objects are easily manipulated . This is not possible with Strings. Strings will not have date manipulating functionality.

  • If we need to know how many seconds there are between two random dates that are 15 days apart. This is not possible with strings.

Lets explore some date Attributes¶

In [6]:
#create date object 
#date(year,month,day)
date_A = date(2020 , 4 , 25)
In [7]:
date_A.day
Out[7]:
25
In [8]:
date_A.year
Out[8]:
2020
In [9]:
date_A.month
Out[9]:
4
There is also a time class in the date module¶
In [8]:
from datetime import date,time

Time is defined using different attributes

hour - minute - second - microsecond

Parsing dates from text¶

In [34]:
#What if we don't have date objects

The reality is often we will not have date objects readymade for us . Most likely we will start working with raw text. And we are going to somehow convert that text into dates.

strptime ==> String Parse Time¶

  • meaning we are starting from a String
  • We are parsing from it time

datetime has a method dedicated to extracting dates out of text.

  • And that method is called strptime

strptime() takes two arguments : the string we are trying to convert and the we pass the format that this string is expressed in

In [29]:
datetime.strptime('10-10-2000' , '%m-%d-%Y')
Out[29]:
datetime.datetime(2000, 10, 10, 0, 0)
In [36]:
datetime.strptime('2019-10-31', '%Y-%m-%d')
Out[36]:
datetime.datetime(2019, 10, 31, 0, 0)
In [37]:
#now we have a datetime object to work with
(datetime.strptime('2019-10-31', '%Y-%m-%d')).day
Out[37]:
31
In [38]:
(datetime.strptime('2019-10-31', '%Y-%m-%d')).year
Out[38]:
2019
In [18]:
#This way we can go ahead and operate on the datetime object
dt_B = datetime.strptime('2019-10-31', '%Y-%m-%d')
In [31]:
dt_B.year
Out[31]:
2019
In [19]:
dt_B.isoformat()
Out[19]:
'2019-10-31T00:00:00'
In [32]:
dt_B.isoformat()
Out[32]:
'2019-10-31T00:00:00'

Another example¶

In [42]:
try_this = "jan 20 2090 4pm"

We need to give the exact format for "jan 20 2090 4pm"

In [33]:
datetime.strptime('jan 20 2090 4pm' , '%b %d %Y %I%p' )
Out[33]:
datetime.datetime(2090, 1, 20, 16, 0)
In [44]:
datetime.strptime(try_this , '%b %d %Y %I%p')
Out[44]:
datetime.datetime(2090, 1, 20, 16, 0)

In [22]:
#Another Example : When there is any character
try_this = "jan 20 2090; 4pm"
In [23]:
datetime.strptime(try_this, '%b %d %Y; %I%p')
Out[23]:
datetime.datetime(2090, 1, 20, 16, 0)

From Datetime to String¶

the strftime() method¶

- This stands for string format time¶

In [36]:
datetime.now()
Out[36]:
datetime.datetime(2023, 1, 10, 22, 50, 15, 297969)
In [31]:
dt = datetime.now()
In [32]:
dt
Out[32]:
datetime.datetime(2023, 1, 13, 15, 57, 28, 780193)
In [54]:
#Let try to condense this datetime into a single year
dt.strftime('%Y')
Out[54]:
'2022'
  • We are capturing year and discarding or losing everything else
In [55]:
#Another string representation of the same date
dt.strftime('Year : %Y; Month : %m ; Day : %d')
Out[55]:
'Year : 2022; Month : 12 ; Day : 11'
In [33]:
#Another string representation of the same date is
dt.strftime('Year : %Y; Month : %m ; Day : %d')
Out[33]:
'Year : 2023; Month : 01 ; Day : 13'

More efficient code¶

You can refer to the format codes that represent both : Stringformat (strftime()) and string parse time (strptime())

In [34]:
dt
Out[34]:
datetime.datetime(2023, 1, 13, 15, 57, 28, 780193)
In [37]:
dt.strftime('%c')
Out[37]:
'Fri Jan 13 15:57:28 2023'
In [56]:
dt.strftime('%c')
Out[56]:
'Sun Dec 11 21:36:16 2022'
In [57]:
#An Alternative Approach
In [60]:
"My data is {:%c}"
Out[60]:
'My data is {:%c}'
In [61]:
"My date is {:%c}".format(dt)
Out[61]:
'My date is Sun Dec 11 21:36:16 2022'

This is how we convert datetime to Strings in Python

The Numpy datetime64 Object¶

Performant datetimes with Numpy¶

https://www.udemy.com/course/the-ultimate-pandas-bootcamp-advanced-python-data-analysis/learn/lecture/19342416#questions/13647656

Lets create a new datetime object

In [38]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
In [40]:
#Instead of a Python datetime , we are now looking at the numpy datetime64 object
np.datetime64('2020-03-04')
Out[40]:
numpy.datetime64('2020-03-04')
In [39]:
#Instead of a Python datetime , we are now looking at the numpy datetime64 object
np.datetime64('2020-03-04')
Out[39]:
numpy.datetime64('2020-03-04')
In [43]:
a = np.datetime64('2020-03-04')
In [42]:
#Creating another datetime object
b = np.datetime64(datetime.now())
In [41]:
b
Out[41]:
numpy.datetime64('2023-01-13T17:52:26.120978')
  • Now we have two datetime objects
  • Now we can conduct operations on them
In [44]:
a
Out[44]:
numpy.datetime64('2020-03-04')
In [45]:
#Starting with 'a' ('2020-03-04') , lets add 10 days
#day 4 has become 14
a + 10
Out[45]:
numpy.datetime64('2020-03-14')
In [46]:
b
Out[46]:
numpy.datetime64('2023-01-10T22:54:57.556694')
In [47]:
#Lets try to add 10 to "b = np.datetime64(datetime.now())" , capturing 12th of December
#numpy.datetime64('2022-12-12T07:52:02.666518')
#If we add 10 to b , we get the same datetime back
b + 10
Out[47]:
numpy.datetime64('2023-01-10T22:54:57.556704')

Since b has a microsecond time unit , we just see some microseconds change

  • because microseconds was the lowest precision here , we see the change in microseconds

We could change the time unit by Re-scaling the numpy datetime

  • If we want to Re-scale our datetime "b" to have a daily timescale
In [48]:
b
Out[48]:
numpy.datetime64('2023-01-10T22:54:57.556694')
In [49]:
b = np.datetime64(b , 'D')
In [50]:
b
Out[50]:
numpy.datetime64('2023-01-10')
  • "D" is for day
  • And we have a Re-scaled datetime ---> "T22:54:57.556694" is gone
In [51]:
#And now if we add 10 to this
b + 10
Out[51]:
numpy.datetime64('2023-01-20')

The power of this numpy datetime approach is ,it allows us to perform efficient vectorized operations on collections of dates.¶

In [46]:
#Lets say we have an array of dates
np.array([
    '2019-02-20',
    '2019-06-20',
    '2090-03-23'
], dtype = np.datetime64)
Out[46]:
array(['2019-02-20', '2019-06-20', '2090-03-23'], dtype='datetime64[D]')
In [47]:
x='2019-02-20'
In [52]:
np.datetime64(x)
Out[52]:
numpy.datetime64('2019-02-20')
In [84]:
#Lets say we have an array of dates
#and we specify the dtype to be "np.datetime64" so that Numpy parses this date for us
np.array([
    '2019-02-20',
    '2019-06-20',
    '2090-03-23'
], dtype = np.datetime64)
Out[84]:
array(['2019-02-20', '2019-06-20', '2090-03-23'], dtype='datetime64[D]')
In [53]:
dates = np.array([
    '2019-02-20',
    '2019-06-20',
    '2090-03-23'
], dtype = np.datetime64)
In [54]:
#Subtract 10 days from each date in the Array
dates - 10
Out[54]:
array(['2019-02-10', '2019-06-10', '2090-03-13'], dtype='datetime64[D]')
  • And this is happening in a vectorized fashion

More Complicated Calculations with Numpy¶

In [57]:
#Get the 10th previous Business date for all the dates in the Array
#This below function primarily calculates Business days
#offsets = -10 ::::Meaning , 10 previous days before
#roll = 'backward' :::: Let say this operation falls on a holiday
#This below function primarily calculates Business days, but what if it falls on a holiday 
#In such situation , do we want to go backward or forward
#In this case the roll parameter specifies that we want to go backward
In [55]:
dates
Out[55]:
array(['2019-02-20', '2019-06-20', '2090-03-23'], dtype='datetime64[D]')
In [58]:
np.busday_offset(dates, offsets = -10 , roll= 'backward')
Out[58]:
array(['2019-02-06', '2019-06-06', '2090-03-09'], dtype='datetime64[D]')

The Pandas TimeStamp¶

In [90]:
#Pandas datetime = python datetime + numpy datetime64
In [59]:
#Lets take a string
"4th of july 1776"
Out[59]:
'4th of july 1776'
  • We want to convert this to a Pandas timestamp
In [60]:
pd.Timestamp('4th of july 1776')
Out[60]:
Timestamp('1776-07-04 00:00:00')
In [93]:
#This code will give the same output
#When we have dates like this , there is ambiguity , if the first number
#represents the month or the day so , we end up getting 7th of April instead of 3th of July
pd.Timestamp('4/7/1776')
Out[93]:
Timestamp('1776-04-07 00:00:00')

When we have dates like this , there is ambiguity , if the first number represents the month or the day so , we end up getting 7th of April instead of 3th of July¶

For this we have a "dayfirst" parameter in the pd module

In [94]:
pd.to_datetime('4/7/1776' , dayfirst = True)
Out[94]:
Timestamp('1776-07-04 00:00:00')
  • Notice in all three cases , we got "Timestamp"
  • what is this Timestamp ?
  • TimeStamp is a fundamental building block of all Time operations in Pandas
In [95]:
pdts = pd.to_datetime('4/7/1776' , dayfirst = True)
In [98]:
pdts
Out[98]:
Timestamp('1776-07-04 00:00:00')
  • Now we got the date for july
In [96]:
pdts.day_name()
Out[96]:
'Thursday'
In [97]:
pdts.day
Out[97]:
4
In [99]:
#The month of July has how many days
pdts.days_in_month
Out[99]:
31
In [100]:
#What quarter did pdts fall in
pdts.quarter
Out[100]:
3

We can also represent this date in a Three item tuple , containing the year, the week and the day of the week containing the isocalendar() method

In [101]:
pdts.isocalendar()
Out[101]:
(1776, 27, 4)

Summarize :¶

- The TimeStamp Object in Pandas comes with its own methods and Attributes and is the basic building 
block of all operations involving time and date in Pandas.
- It serves as a replacement for the Python datetime Module and under the hood its based on 
the Numpy's 64 time.

Difference betweeb Timedelta and DateOffset¶

TimeDelta operates on Absolute Time (meaning , TimeDelta always considers Date to be 24 hours long) whereas DateOffset operates on Calendar time.

  • In other words DateOffset is Calendar aware. It takes into consideration , things like Day light Saving .
  • Depending on the time Zone and Time of the Year , a Day may be 23, 24 or 25 hours long
In [215]:
#We will make this Time stanp time zone aware by passing the Time zone to the "tz" parameter

Resampling TimeSeries¶

The Process of altering the freiquency of a TimeSeries is known as Re-sampling .

  • In this example we are going from Daily to monthly
  • We are Resampling the Fequency down , which is also known as "downsampling"
  • In Pandas we do this using the "resample()" method

https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/user_guide/timeseries.html

Upsample and Interpolation¶

In [233]:
#resample frequency down ---> downsample, eg: D(aily) --> M(onthly)
#resample frequency up ---> upsample, eg: D(aily) ---> H(ourly)
#downsample ---> Condense many to fewer
#Upsample ---> Few to many more
In [234]:
#In our brent series we have the Daily Price Observations
#Lets try to resample to 8 Hour period
brent.resample('8H').mean()
Out[234]:

21628 rows 1 columns

  • Pandas returns NANs where there is no data

How to solve this issue? , How can we fill those Gaps?¶

The Answer is : "Interpolation"¶

Interpolation deals with the theory and method to create new Data points out of range of known Observations

Linear Interpolation¶

We want to fill these gaps using Linear Interpolation:

In [238]:
#example 
#23.95 , NAN , NAN , 23.72
#OR
#23.95 , N1 , N2 , 23.72
  • So, how much is the value changing ?
  • That will be the difference between the Last Price and the First Price divided by 3
In [236]:
23.72 - 23.95 / 3
Out[236]:
15.736666666666665
In [ ]:
Key Assumption in Linear Interpolation  : "Distances are Equal" OR "the Items are equally spaced"
In [245]:
#Lets assign it to diff
diff = (23.72 - 23.95) / 3
In [246]:
N1 = 23.95 + diff
In [247]:
N1
Out[247]:
23.87333333333333
In [248]:
N2 = N1 + diff
In [249]:
N2
Out[249]:
23.796666666666663
In [250]:
#And the final Price is 
N2 + diff
Out[250]:
23.719999999999995

And we are back to our second price : 23.72

In [251]:
round(N2 + diff , 2)
Out[251]:
23.72
  • We can say that we can linearly Interpolated the Pricing for each 8 hour interval between JAN 4 and JAN 5
  • Obviously we do not want to do all this manually

Rolling Windows¶

In [265]:

Rolling Window : IS a collection of observations combined with an Aggregate Function. Its called Rolling because it rolls forward.

If we have "size : 3" , we apply the aggregation to 3 Observations then we move forward , then apply the aggregation to the next 3 and then move forward to the next 3....and so on.

In [266]:
#window size : 3
#aggfunc : mean()
In [269]:
#This gives us the SUM of first 3 observations, then divide by 3
#And we have our first observation in the window
(brent.iloc[0] + brent.iloc[1] + brent.iloc[2] ) / 3
Out[269]:
Price    23.74
dtype: float64
In [270]:
#Then we select the next three observations
(brent.iloc[1] + brent.iloc[2] + brent.iloc[3] ) / 3
Out[270]:
Price    23.54
dtype: float64
In [271]:
#We can simply say :
